Certainly! Below is a simple HTML demo of the game Flappy Bird. Please note that this is a static demonstration and does not include game logic or animations.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Flappy Bird Demo</title>
    <style>
        #game {
            position: relative;
            width: 336px;
            height: 480px;
            background-color: #bbc;
            perspective: 600px;
        }
        .bird {
            position: absolute;
            left: 50px;
            top: 50px;
            width: 50px;
            height: 35px;
            background: url('bird.png') no-repeat;
            background-size: contain;
            transform: rotate(-5deg);
            transition: transform 0.1s ease-in-out;
        }
        .pipe {
            position: absolute;
            width: 80px;
            height: 400px;
            background-color: #f80;
            transform: rotate(45deg);
            transition: transform 2s ease-in-out;
        }
        #game .pipe:first-child {
            left: 0;
            transform: translateY(-410px) translateZ(400px);
        }
        #game .pipe:last-child {
            left: 256px;
            transform: translateY(-390px) translateZ(400px);
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="game">
        <div class="bird"></div>
        <div class="pipe"></div>
        <div class="pipe"></div>
    </div>
    <script>
        // This is a simplified script that just places the bird and pipes initially.
        // In a real game, you would have game loop, collision detection, and bird/pipe movement logic.
        const bird = document.querySelector('.bird');
        const pipes = document.querySelectorAll('.pipe');

        // Place the bird in the middle
        bird.style.transform = `translateY(${Math.random() * 100}px)`;

        // Place the pipes
        pipes.forEach(pipe => {
            pipe.style.transform = `translateY(${Math.random() * 300}px)`;
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

To play the game, you would need a sprite for the bird and pipes. In the example above, replace `bird.png` with your bird sprite image url, and set the height and width of the `.pipe` class accordingly to match your pipe sprite. This demo only sets the initial positions of the bird and pipes. To make the game interactive, you would need to add JavaScript to handle user input (like pressing the space bar to make the bird fly) and implement the game logic, obstacles, scoring, and collision detection.
